ding as history, his work riddled with guesswork, errors, and outright fabrications. This volume aims to challenge such views of Gaimar by providing the first holistic study of his Estoire's incisive commentary upon kingship: its virtues, vices and conflicting models, as applied to rulers such as Edgar "the Peaceable", Cnut, and the ill-fated William Rufus. One good king, for Gaimar, is much like another. A bad king, by contrast, is vividly characterised as ineffectual, tyrannical, or both. Gaimar, a product of that extraordinary period in medieval English culture often termed the "twelfth-century Renaissance'" blends history with literary tropes to yield a sophisticated account of the invasions, betrayals, and familial conflicts that shaped his England's history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aMedieval Literature. 4aMilitary History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon Chronicle.  aCnut.  aKingship.  aWilliam Rufus.  ahistorical representation.  ahistory writing.  ahistory.  amedieval history.  amonarchs.  apower.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800103269?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800103269423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800103269/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles